{"parse":{"title":"Dirty realism","pageid":4783841,"revid":815966409,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Dirty realism</b> is a term coined by <a href=\"/wiki/Bill_Buford\" title=\"Bill Buford\">Bill Buford</a> of <i><a href=\"/wiki/Granta\" title=\"Granta\">Granta</a></i> magazine to define a <a href=\"/wiki/North_America\" title=\"North America\">North American</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Literary_movement\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Literary movement\">literary movement</a>. Writers in this sub-category of <a href=\"/wiki/Literary_realism\" title=\"Literary realism\">realism</a> are said to depict the seamier or more <a href=\"/wiki/Mundane\" title=\"Mundane\">mundane</a> aspects of ordinary life in spare, unadorned language.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> The term formed the title of the Summer 1983 edition of <i><a href=\"/wiki/Granta\" title=\"Granta\">Granta</a></i>, for which Buford wrote an explanatory introduction:\n</p>\n<dl><dd>\"Dirty Realism is the fiction of a new generation of American authors. They write about the belly-side of contemporary life \u2013 a deserted husband, an unwed mother, a car thief, a pickpocket, a drug addict \u2013 but they write about it with a disturbing detachment, at times verging on comedy. Understated, ironic, sometimes savage, but insistently compassionate, these stories constitute a new voice in fiction.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup></dd></dl>\n<p>Sometimes considered a variety of <a href=\"/wiki/Literary_minimalism\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Literary minimalism\">literary minimalism</a>, dirty realism is characterized by an economy with words and a focus on surface description. Writers working within the genre tend to avoid <a href=\"/wiki/Adverb\" title=\"Adverb\">adverbs</a>, extended <a href=\"/wiki/Metaphor\" title=\"Metaphor\">metaphor</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Internal_monologue\" title=\"Internal monologue\">internal monologue</a>, instead allowing objects and context to dictate meaning. Characters are shown in ordinary, unremarkable occupations, and often a lack of resources and money that creates an internal desperation.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>After Buford's categorisation, the definition has expanded to include, according to Michael Hemmingson, as the movement's \"godfather\" <a href=\"/wiki/Charles_Bukowski\" title=\"Charles Bukowski\">Charles Bukowski</a> (1920\u20131994), as well as those who appeared in <i>Granta</i> 8, including <a href=\"/wiki/Raymond_Carver\" title=\"Raymond Carver\">Raymond Carver</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> (1938\u20131988), <a href=\"/wiki/Tobias_Wolff\" title=\"Tobias Wolff\">Tobias Wolff</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> (b. 1945), <a href=\"/wiki/Richard_Ford\" title=\"Richard Ford\">Richard Ford</a> (b. 1944), <a href=\"/wiki/Larry_Brown_(author)\" title=\"Larry Brown (author)\">Larry Brown</a> (1951\u20132004), <a href=\"/wiki/Frederick_Barthelme\" title=\"Frederick Barthelme\">Frederick Barthelme</a> (b. 1943), <a href=\"/wiki/Cormac_McCarthy\" title=\"Cormac McCarthy\">Cormac McCarthy</a> (b. 1933), <a href=\"/wiki/Pedro_Juan_Guti%C3%A9rrez\" title=\"Pedro Juan Guti\u00e9rrez\">Pedro Juan Guti\u00e9rrez</a> (b. 1950), <a href=\"https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fernando_Vel%C3%A1zquez_Medina\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"es:Fernando Vel\u00e1zquez Medina\">Fernando Vel\u00e1zquez Medina</a> (b. 1951), <a href=\"/wiki/Carson_McCullers\" title=\"Carson McCullers\">Carson McCullers</a> (1917\u20131967), and <a href=\"/wiki/Jayne_Anne_Phillips\" title=\"Jayne Anne Phillips\">Jayne Anne Phillips</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> (b. 1952). These authors have rarely accepted or self-applied this term, despite close associations and affinities.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Dirty_realism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Kmart_realism\" title=\"Kmart realism\">Kmart realism</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Grunge_lit\" title=\"Grunge lit\">Grunge lit</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Dirty_realism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\"Definition: Dirty Realism\". Online dictionary service in English, Spanish, German and other languages by. 20 July 2008. 30 Dec. 2008 &lt;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://dictionary.reverso.net/english-definitions/dirty%20realism\">http://dictionary.reverso.net/english-definitions/dirty%20realism</a>&gt;.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.granta.com/Archive/8\">Granta Magazine, Summer 1983</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.themodernnovel.org/movements/dirty/\">themodernnovel.org</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a href=\"/wiki/Michael_Hemmingson\" title=\"Michael Hemmingson\">Hemmingson, Michael</a>. The Dirty Realism Duo: Charles Bukowski &amp; Raymond Carver. California: Borgo Press, 2008.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.metro.co.uk/metrolife/books/article.html?in_article_id=241644&amp;in_page_id=28\">Wolf, Tobias. \"Our Story Begins excels in dirty realism | Metro.co.uk.\" | Metro.co.uk. 20 July 2008. 30 Dec. 2008</a> </span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Jarvis, Brian, <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_hb351/is_2001_Annual/ai_n28890341/\">\"How Dirty is Jayne Anne Phillips?\"</a> Yearbook of English Studies, 2001 Annual.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Dirty_realism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.facebook.com/groups/dirtyrealism/\">Facebook group dedicated to Dirty Realism</a></li></ul>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:P_literature.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/P_literature.svg/30px-P_literature.svg.png\" width=\"30\" height=\"27\" srcset=\"//upload.w